[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah.

428
00:41:49,620 --> 00:41:54,862
[SPEAKER_07]: Um, so this one's actually for the city administration, I guess, for Alicia.

429
00:41:55,562 --> 00:41:59,943
[SPEAKER_07]: So, um, there was a mention by the applicant in the last meeting.

430
00:42:00,696 --> 00:42:14,452
[SPEAKER_07]: about a willingness when they come to the before the subsidizing agency for final approval to possibly institute some sort of local preference option, which is not in our purview.

431
00:42:15,614 --> 00:42:20,680
[SPEAKER_07]: But I was just reading through the 40 B manual and it mentioned their

432
00:42:21,692 --> 00:42:26,736
[SPEAKER_07]: that the onus is on Medford to justify the need for that.

433
00:42:26,837 --> 00:42:44,091
[SPEAKER_07]: So I've heard a lot of residents claim that Medford needs local preference and you know I have my own partially informed belief on the matter but I'm wondering if sometime

434
00:42:45,888 --> 00:43:09,878
[SPEAKER_07]: midway through this hearing, if the planning department would be able to investigate and document any need for local preference, propose a reasonable percentage of local preference units, and evaluate whether any proposed local preference plan will have a disparate impact on people and classes protected under the Federal Fair Housing Act.

435
00:43:10,398 --> 00:43:15,200
[SPEAKER_07]: I believe if we do that, that the board will have the information it needs to decide

436
00:43:16,087 --> 00:43:23,231
[SPEAKER_07]: whether to impose that as a condition, which may ultimately be overturned by the subsidizing agency.

437
00:43:23,291 --> 00:43:30,194
[SPEAKER_07]: But if we don't do the work up front, it's unlikely, as I understand it, that that would be approved.

438
00:43:34,396 --> 00:43:36,277
[SPEAKER_01]: Danielle's prepared to respond to that.

439
00:43:36,857 --> 00:43:39,199
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, Danielle, go ahead.

440
00:43:39,219 --> 00:43:40,599
[SPEAKER_06]: Hi, apologies, my camera's off.

441
00:43:40,659 --> 00:43:42,580
[SPEAKER_06]: I am home, sick with COVID, so.

442
00:43:42,640 --> 00:43:43,981
[SPEAKER_04]: No worries, thank you for joining us.

443
00:43:45,163 --> 00:43:52,684
[SPEAKER_06]: Um, so we regularly get, um, 70% local preference, which is the maximum that DHCD allows.

444
00:43:52,704 --> 00:44:02,466
[SPEAKER_06]: Um, we have, um, you know, met their requirements for our local demographics to get that maximum.

445
00:44:02,526 --> 00:44:11,768
[SPEAKER_06]: So for all our local initiative projects, which is, um, our inclusionary units, we do 70%, and we have never had any pushback on that.

446
00:44:13,465 --> 00:44:15,766
[SPEAKER_06]: So I expect that's what we would do for this.

447
00:44:15,906 --> 00:44:27,711
[SPEAKER_06]: But just to keep in mind that local preference is for folks that live here, work here, have children to go to school here, and you can live here for a day.

448
00:44:28,351 --> 00:44:29,631
[SPEAKER_06]: And that gives you local preference.

449
00:44:30,532 --> 00:44:36,294
[SPEAKER_06]: If someone's grown children have, you know, they're from here and they've left, they don't have local preference.

450
00:44:36,314 --> 00:44:40,336
[SPEAKER_06]: So sometimes local preference isn't what people think it is.

451
00:44:42,358 --> 00:44:47,219
[SPEAKER_06]: So just to keep that in mind, that there can be unintended consequences with the local preference as well.

452
00:44:48,079 --> 00:44:48,579
[SPEAKER_04]: Interesting.

453
00:44:49,999 --> 00:44:50,679
[SPEAKER_07]: Through the chair.

454
00:44:50,699 --> 00:44:52,140
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, go ahead.

455
00:44:52,820 --> 00:44:55,020
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, thank you, Danielle.

456
00:44:55,280 --> 00:44:56,420
[SPEAKER_07]: That's good information.

457
00:44:56,440 --> 00:45:10,103
[SPEAKER_07]: The main thing for me is if at any point in this hearing, we're gonna be discussing whether or not to impose a local preference condition on this project,

458
00:45:11,005 --> 00:45:16,090
[SPEAKER_07]: I would need some documented case in writing.

459
00:45:16,190 --> 00:45:23,957
[SPEAKER_07]: So, like, I wouldn't feel comfortable imposing such a condition if it was just based on a hunch.

460
00:45:24,377 --> 00:45:32,605
[SPEAKER_07]: So my request is just that the planning department document whether there is or isn't a need and

461
00:45:33,352 --> 00:45:48,696
[SPEAKER_07]: and some of these other factors, and maybe the answer is really quick and it's along the lines of what you just shared, but I would just like a responsive document at some point in the hearing so that when we're having that discussion, we can make an informed decision as a board.

462
00:45:49,537 --> 00:45:58,919
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, I can forward you the most recent local preference justification, which is what is required by DHCD whenever we require that.

463
00:45:59,640 --> 00:46:00,480
[SPEAKER_07]: Wonderful, thank you.

464
00:46:02,238 --> 00:46:02,779
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, thanks.

465
00:46:03,159 --> 00:46:03,640
[SPEAKER_04]: Andre, go ahead.

466
00:46:05,502 --> 00:46:12,611
[SPEAKER_08]: Just related to that is I'm wondering whether, you know, there's a, we should be looking.

467
00:46:14,594 --> 00:46:16,897
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, Andre, I just accidentally muted you.

468
00:46:16,917 --> 00:46:17,317
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm sorry.

469
00:46:17,337 --> 00:46:20,081
[SPEAKER_04]: Go ahead.

470
00:46:20,668 --> 00:46:21,808
[SPEAKER_08]: Sorry, I've spoken too much.

471
00:46:22,149 --> 00:46:24,009
[SPEAKER_04]: No, no, I was just trying to put your hand down.

472
00:46:24,089 --> 00:46:24,549
[SPEAKER_04]: Go ahead.

473
00:46:26,130 --> 00:46:31,851
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm wondering whether we should, you know, should we review a fair housing marketing plan?

474
00:46:31,891 --> 00:46:38,193
[SPEAKER_08]: So I don't know, Danielle, if this is something you can speak to as well.

475
00:46:38,233 --> 00:46:49,876
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, usually the onus is on, well, we haven't done a 40B in Medford, so I'm not sure if the process is different than the regular process, which is through the local initiative program.

476
00:46:50,481 --> 00:47:05,325
[SPEAKER_06]: where the developer usually hiring a consultant would create a Fair Housing Marketing Plan, Affirmative Fair Housing Marketing Plan, which has to be approved by DHCD and as part of the application.

477
00:47:05,965 --> 00:47:07,085
[SPEAKER_06]: Judy, correct me if I'm wrong.

478
00:47:07,145 --> 00:47:11,986
[SPEAKER_06]: I know the process is slightly different for a comprehensive permit.

479
00:47:12,086 --> 00:47:14,007
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm not sure the order of operations here.

480
00:47:14,507 --> 00:47:19,228
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, so typically the Affirmative Fair Housing Marketing Plan is prepared by the applicant

481
00:47:19,900 --> 00:47:27,123
[SPEAKER_05]: and submitted to the subsidizing agency as part of the whole final approval process, which is post-comprehensive permit.

482
00:47:29,244 --> 00:47:36,967
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, the city or town will typically get a copy of that to look at, but it doesn't happen now, it happens later.

483
00:47:36,987 --> 00:47:45,411
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, and it's not something that generally the ZBA has comments or suggestions about?

484
00:47:46,353 --> 00:47:51,738
[SPEAKER_05]: So I can just tell you what I've written into permits that that I've drafted.

485
00:47:53,039 --> 00:48:05,431
[SPEAKER_05]: That the applicant needs to provide the city with a copy of the plan two weeks before or some period before it's submitted into the subsidizing agency so that city staff and officials can at least look at it.

486
00:48:08,368 --> 00:48:25,049
[SPEAKER_05]: And I typically don't write local preference into, I'm just speaking from my practice, you know, you can take this up with town council if you need to, but I typically don't write local preference into a permit because the board really doesn't have any jurisdiction over tenant selection.

487
00:48:26,262 --> 00:48:43,068
[SPEAKER_05]: So what I suggest is that, you know, you have it referred to the city for review before the applicant files with the subsidizing agency and let the policy people, the mayor's office, the planning department or whomever, determine whether local preference should be required for the particular project.

488
00:48:43,169 --> 00:48:44,949
[SPEAKER_05]: It sort of gets the CBA out of the middle.

489
00:48:48,210 --> 00:48:49,091
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, thanks, Judy.

490
00:48:49,711 --> 00:48:49,971
[SPEAKER_04]: Bill?

491
00:48:53,272 --> 00:48:54,053
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you, Madam Chair.

492
00:48:55,767 --> 00:49:10,003
[SPEAKER_11]: Again, this issue has come up, and I know I made comments about it last time, and I still stand by my original opinion that the affordable units should be

493
00:49:10,482 --> 00:49:13,324
[SPEAKER_11]: incorporated into the approved plans.

494
00:49:13,384 --> 00:49:19,088
[SPEAKER_11]: And the reason being is that that it's otherwise not equitable.

495
00:49:19,488 --> 00:49:26,933
[SPEAKER_11]: If the developer gets to choose which units they're saying could be affordable, you know, technically you could end up with

496
00:49:27,600 --> 00:49:40,309
[SPEAKER_11]: all of the affordable units having something simple like four micro countertops and carpet, and maybe in locations next to a gym or a pool or a place that another person may not necessarily want.

497
00:49:40,389 --> 00:49:45,113
[SPEAKER_11]: So in my experience in 40B, there's always been a floor plan matrix.

498
00:49:45,676 --> 00:49:54,038
[SPEAKER_11]: showing the designated affordable units, that becomes part of the order and gets written into the order and then that way there it's enforceable.

499
00:49:54,559 --> 00:50:02,281
[SPEAKER_11]: Otherwise, that takes the enforcement out of my hands once the building permit has been issued and a certificate of occupancy has been requested.

500
00:50:03,001 --> 00:50:08,363
[SPEAKER_11]: Um, so I, I, I completely disagree, um, with the fact that we leave this up to the developer.

501
00:50:08,383 --> 00:50:10,184
[SPEAKER_11]: This, this should not be up to the developer.

502
00:50:10,544 --> 00:50:18,708
[SPEAKER_11]: This is a function of the zoning board of appeals and the enforcement of the, of the fair housing, the, the, uh, the equitable housing.

503
00:50:18,808 --> 00:50:30,333
[SPEAKER_11]: So, uh, I'm prepared to provide you with a little bit more, uh, background written to it, um, in my next, um, um, set of comments, but, um, I just wanted to kind of throw that out there.

504
00:50:30,787 --> 00:50:32,510
[SPEAKER_11]: All right, that I'm still in disagreement.

505
00:50:32,630 --> 00:50:38,159
[SPEAKER_11]: And it's been my experience that that is decided by the ZBA and enforced by the building inspector.

506
00:50:38,179 --> 00:50:40,142
[SPEAKER_04]: OK, Bill, thank you.

507
00:50:40,242 --> 00:50:43,467
[SPEAKER_04]: I know that I remember that last time I think we had some differing opinions.

508
00:50:44,230 --> 00:50:46,191
[SPEAKER_04]: with Judy and Daniela get you in one second.

