554
00:53:23,561 --> 00:53:32,006
[SPEAKER_06]: So, we would want these to be floating units, because when applicants are when when tenants go over income, they don't get kicked out.

555
00:53:32,647 --> 00:53:35,128
[SPEAKER_06]: They usually go up to I think 140% of airy mean income before.

556
00:53:39,129 --> 00:53:43,830
[SPEAKER_06]: the units would change or convert to a market rate unit.

557
00:53:44,491 --> 00:53:56,514
[SPEAKER_06]: So if an income eligible tenant was in the initial lease up and then they go over income, then it would revert to a market rate.

558
00:53:57,653 --> 00:54:02,177
[SPEAKER_06]: And if they weren't floating units, then we wouldn't have, we'd be short an affordable unit.

559
00:54:02,797 --> 00:54:12,666
[SPEAKER_06]: So what it would generally is in these regulatory agreements is that the next available or comparable unit would then become an affordable unit.

560
00:54:13,026 --> 00:54:16,269
[SPEAKER_06]: So I always insist that they're floating.

561
00:54:16,609 --> 00:54:21,293
[SPEAKER_06]: I've had developers want them to be fixed because that's advantageous to them.

562
00:54:21,313 --> 00:54:21,373
[SPEAKER_06]: And

563
00:54:23,371 --> 00:54:28,295
[SPEAKER_06]: floating is generally better for the city and to keep the units.

564
00:54:29,135 --> 00:54:45,066
[SPEAKER_06]: And at the time, and again, I don't know about the comprehensive permit steps at this stage, but for local initiative program units, when we submit for those to be approved, that's when I would review the floor plans.

565
00:54:45,967 --> 00:54:52,732
[SPEAKER_06]: And usually, you know, I make suggestions and ask that they be moved so that they're

566
00:54:53,987 --> 00:55:07,952
[SPEAKER_06]: you know, proportionately distributed throughout the development, that, you know, it's the same, it's a percentage of the three, two, one, or studios for the bedrooms, and that they're not in the least desirable locations so that they're, you know, distributed.

567
00:55:08,932 --> 00:55:16,775
[SPEAKER_06]: So there is staff input, and developers often change their floor plans at our requests.

568
00:55:18,809 --> 00:55:31,594
[SPEAKER_05]: I would have to endorse that, Danielle that that is exactly the way it works, that the units need to be able to float so you don't end up with someone or household whose income exceeds 140% of AMI and now they have to leave.

569
00:55:34,175 --> 00:55:35,795
[SPEAKER_05]: That's just not in anybody's interest.

570
00:55:35,835 --> 00:55:40,337
[SPEAKER_05]: So the floating unit is really what I see in almost all the rental developments I've seen.

571
00:55:40,897 --> 00:55:45,258
[SPEAKER_05]: If someone wants to do a fixed floor plan, that's between them and the subsidizing agency.

572
00:55:45,338 --> 00:55:50,499
[SPEAKER_05]: But I think the other thing I want to just point out is it's never the developer who gets to make the final decision.

573
00:55:50,539 --> 00:55:51,799
[SPEAKER_05]: It's the subsidizing agency.

574
00:55:52,620 --> 00:55:53,920
[SPEAKER_05]: So during final approval,

575
00:55:54,700 --> 00:56:04,185
[SPEAKER_05]: you know, when things are being nailed down before, you know, as part of the whole regulatory agreement and so forth, the developer's gonna have to show the subsidizing agency, here's where I wanna put my affordable units.

576
00:56:04,245 --> 00:56:07,426
[SPEAKER_05]: And the subsidizing agencies are gonna approve it or they're gonna push back.

577
00:56:08,287 --> 00:56:11,188
[SPEAKER_05]: And I've had experience of subsidizing agency pushing back.

578
00:56:11,248 --> 00:56:17,952
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think people should just understand the interest in fair housing is not just at the local level, it's certainly at the state level as well.

